SIMPLE: rumination
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rumination
<hw>Ru`mi*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>ruminatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>rumination</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act or process of ruminating, or chewing the cud; the habit of
chewing the cud.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Rumination</qex> is given to animals to enable them at once
to lay up a great store of food, and afterward to chew it.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being disposed to ruminate or ponder;
deliberate meditation or reflection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Retiring full of <qex>rumination</qex> sad.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The regurgitation of food from
the stomach after it has been swallowed, -- occasionally observed as a
morbid phenomenon in man.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruminative</ent>⟦br⟧
